text: Inactivation of Flavoenzyme-Encoding Gene flsO1 in Fluostatin Biosynthesis Leads to Diversiﬁed Angucyclinone Derivatives Chunfang Yang, Changsheng Zhang,* and Wenjun Zhang* the ﬂavoenzyme-encoding gene ABSTRACT: Inactivation of f lsO1 in ﬂuostatin biosynthesis led to the isolation of four new angucyclinone derivatives (11, 12, 14, and 15), among which ﬂuostarenes A (14) and B (15) featured the unprecedented 6/6/ 5/6/6 pentacyclic skeleton with fusion of a benzo[b]ﬂuorene and a six-membered lactone ring. Both 14 and 15 were putatively generated via quinone methide-mediated nonenzymatic reactions. Fluostarene B (15) exhibited cytotoxicity against several cancer cell lines with IC50 values ranging from 7 to 10 μM. Fluostarenes A (14), B (15), and PK1 (16) showed α-glucosidase inhibition activity with IC50 of 0.89, 1.58, and 0.13 μM, respectively. Successful complementation of the Δf lsO1 mutant with alpK from kinamycin biosynthesis suggests that FlsO1 should function equivalently to AlpK as a putative C-5 hydroxylase.

Benzoﬂuorene-containing atypical angucyclines are a growing family of natural products, such as kinamycins,1 lomaiviticins,2 nenestatins,3 and ﬂuostatins (e.g., FSTs 1−5)4 (Figure 1). lomaiviticin A displays signiﬁcantly potent Representatively, cytotoxic activities against multifarious tumor cells.5,6 Recent biosynthetic studies on this family of compounds have led to the identiﬁcation of the biosynthesis gene clusters (BGCs) of kinamycins (alp),7,8 lomaiviticins (lom),9,10 nenestatin A (nes),3 and ﬂuostatins (f ls11 or f luo12), revealing a type II polyketide synthase (PKS) origin. Subsequently, genetic and biochemical experiments have demonstrated key steps and features in the biosynthesis of benzo[b]ﬂuorene-containing angucyclines,13 for example, the new starter-unit-generating strategy in lomaiviticin biosynthesis,14 the α/β hydrolases (Alp1U/Lom6)-catalyzed epoxide ring opening,15,16 the acetyltransferase Alp2D-mediated acetylations and discrete oﬄoading thioesterase in kinamycins,8,17 and the unusual N− N bond forming strategy in kinamycin biosynthesis.18 Particularly, the ﬂavin-dependent oxidase AlpJ was functionally characterized to catalyze the B-ring cleavage and contraction reactions from dehydrorabelomycin (6) to yield the benzo- ﬂuorene intermediate 7 during kinamycin biosynthesis, and the ﬂavoenzyme AlpK was deduced to confer a subsequent C-5 hydroxylation of 7 to produce hydroquinone-kinobscurinone (8) (Figure 1).19,20

In contrast, the biosynthesis of benzo[a]ﬂuorene-containing ﬂuostatins (FSTs) was less investigated. FSTs have been isolation,12,21 heterologous structurally expanded by natural Cite This: https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.joc.0c02517 © XXXX American Chemical Society Chunyan Fang, Liping Zhang, Siqiang Chen, Qingbo Zhang, expression of the FST biosynthetic gene cluster (BGC),22−24 and manipulation of the biosynthetic genes.25 The ﬂavoenzyme FlsO2 was characterized as a dual-functional oxygenase, similar to JadH,26 to convert prejadomycin to dehydrorabelomycin, and the α/β hydrolase FlsH was shown as a deacylase to remove acyl groups from acyl ﬂuostatins,23 in contrast to the epoxide hydrolyzing function of its homologous enzymes Alp1U and Lom6.16 Herein, we report the inactivation of f lsO1, encoding an oxygenase homologous to AlpK,19 and the isolation, structure elucidation, and bioactivity evaluation of four new compounds from the f lsO1 inactivation mutants. More importantly, we demonstrated that the complementation of the Δf lsO1 mutant with either f lsO1 or alpK recovered the production of FSTs, implicating that FlsO1 should function equivalently to AlpK. To investigate the function of flsO1 in FST biosynthesis, f lsO1 was inactivated by an insertional mutation in Micromonospora rosaria SCSIO N160 (Figure 2A, Table S1, Table S2, Figure S1), the producer of FSTs 1−5, and dehydrorabelomycin (6) (Figure 1). Gephyromycin D (11) was obtained as brownish yellow cube crystals (Figure 2C). The molecular formula of 11 was determined as C19H16O8 (m/z 371.0774 [M − H]−, calcd 371.0772; Figure S4) by high-resolution electrospray ioniza- tion mass spectroscopy (HRESIMS). The 1D and 2D NMR spectroscopic data of 11 (Figure S4, Table 1) were highly similar to those of gephyromycins28,29 and gephysulfuromy- cin.30 The diﬀerence was that the ethyl group in gephysulfur- omycin was replaced by a singlet methyl (δ C 24.6) in 11. This assignment was supported by HMBC correlations from H3-13 to C-2 and C-4. Additionally, the deshielded resonance of C-3 (δ C 77.8, Δ 22.1 ppm) in 11 revealed the presence of the ether bridge between C-3 and C-12a in 11 instead of the thioether bridge in gephysulfuromycin. The cis-orientation of 4a-OH and 12b-OH was assigned according to the NOESY correlation between them (Figure S4). Finally, the structure of 11 was determined by the single crystal X-ray crystallographic analysis with Cu Kα radiation (CCDC 2011160) (Figure 3), and its absolute conﬁguration was established to be 3S,4aS,12aR,12bR upon a Flack parameter value of −0.14 (13) (Figure 2C, Figure 3, Table S4).

As expected, the production of FSTs 1−5 was restored by the complementation of f lsO1 in the Δf lsO1i mutant (Figure S9). Interestingly, the Δf lsO1i mutant to produce FSTs 1−5 (Figure S9). This fact meant that FlsO1 should catalyze the C-5 hydroxylation of 7 to give 8 in the biosynthesis pathway of FSTs, the same as that of AlpK in kinamycin biosynthesis (Figure 1). abelomycin (6) was shown to display cytotoxic activity against four tumor cell lines (SF-268, MCF-7, HepG2, and A549) with IC50 values of 0.38−1.08 μM, better than the positive control adriamycin (Table 3). Fluostarene B (15) showed moderate inhibitory activity to the four tumor cell lines, with IC50 values of 7−10 μM. No cytotoxic activities were found for 11−12 and 16. None of these compounds exhibited obviously antibacterial activities toward four pathogenic bacteria, including Staph- ylococcus aureus ATCC 29213, methicillin-resistant S. aureus (MRSA) shhs-A1, Vibrio alginolyticus 13214, and Acinetobacter baumannii ATCC 19606 (Table S7). Interestingly, 14−16 were found to be active against α-glucosidase, a target for treating diabetes,32 with IC50 values of 0.89, 1.58, and 0.13 μM (Table 3), respectively, although far below the IC50 value of 0.015 μM of the positive control acarbose.33 The function of α-glucosidase is to produce glucose through hydrolyzing disaccharide, the inhibition of which will decrease the concentration of blood glucose, as such to provide an eﬀective way to treat type 2 diabetes mellitus.34 Biosynthetically, we proposed that compounds 11−12 and 14−16 were shunt products from biosynthetic intermediates in the FST biosynthetic pathway (Scheme 1, Figure S10). Gephyromycin D (11) was likely derived from prejadomycin through an epoxide intermediate, similar to that proposed for gephyromycin (Scheme 1, Figure S10).28 6-Hydroxyfridamycin E (12) was a hydroxyl derivative of fridamycin E,35 which was previously proposed to be generated from an early intermediate UWM6 by a Baeyer−Villiger reaction at the A-

In conclusion, the inactivation of f lsO1 by either in situ insertional mutagenesis or in-frame deletion in a heterologous host harboring the intact f ls BGC led to mutants that aﬀorded four new compounds, gephyromycins D (11), 6-hydroxyfrida- mycin E (12), and ﬂuostarenes A (14) and B (15). Both 14 and 15 featured the unique 6/6/5/6/6 pentacyclic skeleton, with a benzo[b]ﬂuorene core fused to a six-membered lactone ring. General Method for Constructing In-Frame Deletion Mutant S. coelicolor M1154-2 (Δf lsO1i). The 1425 bp aadA and oriT gene cassette was ampliﬁed from the plasmid pIJ778 with primers of ﬂsO1DF and ﬂsO1DR (Table S2). The resulting “disruption” cassette was gel-puriﬁed and introduced into E. coli BW25113/pIJ790/pCSG5033 to obtain the cosmid pCSG5033/ Δf lsO1, which then was transformed into E. coli BT340, to remove the central part of the disruption cassette via the expressed FLP- recombinase, leaving a 81 bp scar and producing the positive cosmid pCSG5042 (Table S1). Subsequently, pCSG5042 was introduced into E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 and used as the donor strain to conjugate with spores of S. coelicolor M1154. In detail, the donor strain E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002/pCSG5042 was treated according to the above method. Spores of the recipient S. coelicolor M1154 grew in SFM medium (2% soybean powder, 2% mannitol, 1.5−2% agar powder, per 1.0 L liquid medium, pH 7.2−7.4) for 3−5 days. The spores were shocked at 50 °C for 10 min and then allowed to cool down before implicated a similar biosynthetic function of FlsO1 and AlpK as the C-5 hydroxylase of 7. This proposal was further supported by the successful the f lsO1-inactivated mutant by alpK. This study expanded the structure diversity of benzoﬂuorene-derived angucyclinones and shed light on in vitro investigation of functions of FlsO1 and its homologues.

Bacterial Strains, Plasmids, and Reagents. Primer designation, bacterial strains, and plasmids used and constructed in this study are listed in Table S1 and Table S2. The strains Streptomyces coelicolor M1154 and Micromonospora rosaria SCSIO N160 were grown and fermented using the same conditions4,11 as those reported before. Chemicals, enzymes, and other molecular biological reagents were purchased from standard commercial sources and used according to the manufacturers’ recommendations. DNA Isolation, Manipulation, and Sequencing. DNA isolation and manipulation in E. coli, Streptomyces, and M. rosaria SCSIO N160 were carried out according to standard procedures.39 Primers were synthesized at The Beijing Genomics Institute (BGI). PCR ampliﬁcations were carried out on an Authorized Thermal Cycler (Eppendorf AG). DNA sequencing was performed at the iGeneTechTM Biotech Co., Ltd. (Guangzhou), and the Chinese National Genome Center (Shanghai).

General Method for Insertional Mutagenesis of f lsO1 in M. rosaria SCSIO N160. The lambda-RED-mediated gene replacements were performed as standard procedures.40 Details of f lsO1 knockout experiments in M. rosaria SCSIO N160 using a modiﬁed genetic manipulation system41 were described in Figure S1. The 1384 bp aac(3)IV and oriT gene cassette was ampliﬁed from plasmid pIJ773 with primers of ﬂsO1DF and ﬂsO1DR (Table S2). After gel puriﬁcation, coli BW25113/pIJ790/pCSG5001 by transformation to aﬀord the positive cosmid pCSG5013 (Table S1), in which part of the f lsO1 gene was replaced by the aac(3)IV and oriT cassette. The cosmid pCSG5013 was then transformed into E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 and used as the donor strain to conjugate with mycelia of M. rosaria SCSIO N160. Brieﬂy, the donor strain E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002/pCSG5013 was prepared by growth to an OD600 of 0.6−0.8, and then, the cells were washed twice and resuspended in LB medium with a concentration of ca. 5 × 109 cells per mL. Mycelia of the recipient M. rosaria SCSIO N160 were obtained in N1 media (1% starch soluble, 0.4% yeast extracts, 0.2% bacterial peptone, 1% sea salt, per 1.0 L liquid medium, pH 7.2−7.4) for 3−5 days. For each conjugation, 1-fold E. coli cells and 2-fold well-prepared recipients were mixed and spread on ISP4 agar plates for growing 20−22 h at 30 °C. General Method for Complementing S. coelicolor M1154-2 (Δf lsO1i) Mutant with f lsO1 and alpK, Respectively. The erm-f lsO1 was ampliﬁed by overlap complement extension PCR using the corresponding primers in Table S2 with plasmid of pPWW50A and genome of M. rosaria SCSIO N160 as templates. The resulting fragment erm-f lsO1 was then assembled with pPM927 (digested with BamHI) utilizing a One Step Clone Kit (Vazyme Biotech) to generate pCSG5043 (Table S1). The comple- ment plasmid pCSG5044 containing erm-alpK was constructed using the same method as that of pCSG5043; the main diﬀerence was that the genomic DNA of Streptomyces ambofaciens Δalp1U15 was used as the template to amplify alpK. Fermentation and Metabolite Analyses by HPLC. The fermentation of f lsO1 mutants was carried out using a modiﬁed N4 medium (peptone ﬁsh 4 g/L, starch soluble 10 g/L, corn powder 6 g/ L, bacterial peptone 2 g/L, glycerol 5 g/L, CaCO3 2 g/L, sea salt 30 g/L, pH 7.2−7.4) in a 250 mL ﬂask by shaking at 200 rpm and 28 °C for 5−7 days. A total of 15 L of fermentation cultures of Δf lsO1 (inserted mutation) was prepared and separated to supernatants and mycelium by centrifugation. Organic phases were evaporated to dryness under reduced pressure to obtain the crude. X-ray Crystallographic Analysis. Brownish yellow cube crystals of gephyromycin D (11) were obtained in CH3Cl/MeOH, and clear reddish red cube crystals of ﬂuostarene A (14) and ﬂuostarene B (15) were obtained in CH3Cl/MeOH (2:1). The crystal data of all three were recorded on an XtaLAB AFC12 (RINC) Kappa single diﬀractometer with Cu Kα radiation (λ = 1.54178 Å). The crystal was kept at 105(7) K during data collection. Using Olex2, the structure was solved with the ShelXT structure solution program using Intrinsic Phasing and reﬁned with the ShelXL reﬁnement package using Least Squares minimization. Crystallographic data for 11, 14, and 15 have been deposited in the Cambridge Crystallo- graphic Data Center with the deposition numbers CCDC 2011160, CCDC 2024422, and CCDC 2024423 respectively. A copy of the data can be obtained, free of charge, on application to the Director, CCDC, 12 Union Road, Cambridge CB21EZ, U.K. (fax, +44(0)- 1233-336033; email, deposit@ccdc.cam.ac.uk). Detailed crystal data of gephyromycin D (11), ﬂuostarene A (14), and ﬂuostarene B (15) were shown in Table S4, Table S5, and Table S6, respectively.

Bioassays. Antimicrobial activities were measured against four indicator strains, Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 29213, methicillin- resistant S. aureus (MRSA) shhs-A1, Vibrio alginolyticus 13214, and Acinetobacter baumannii ATCC 19606 by the broth microdilution method. Four indicator strains were grown for 16 h on a rotary shaker at 37 °C. Cultures were diluted with sterilized medium to achieve an optical absorbance of 0.04−0.06 at 600 nm and then further diluted 10-fold before adding into 96-well microtiter plates. Three replicates of each compound were tested in dilution series ranging from 64 to 0.125 μg/mL. The lowest concentrations that completely inhibited visible growth of the tested strains were recorded after 18 h of cultivation from three independent experiments. In this assay, DMSO was used as a negative control, and vancomycin was used as a positive control.

The in vitro cytotoxic activities of 6, 11−12, and 14−16 were evaluated against four tumor cell lines, SF-268 (human glioma cell line), MCF-7 (human line), HepG2 (human liver carcinoma cell breast adenocarcinoma cell line), and A549 (human lung adenocarcinoma cell), by the SRB method.42 All of the cells were cultivated in RPMI 1640 medium.43 Cells (180 μL) with a density of 3 × 104 cells mL−1 were seeded onto 96-well plates and incubated for 24 h at 37 °C, 5% CO2. Subsequently, 20 μL of diﬀerent concentrations of 6, 11−12, and 14−16, ranging from 0 to 100 μM in DMSO, were added to each plate well. An equal volume of DMSO was used as a negative control. After a further incubation for 72 h, the cell monolayers were ﬁxed with 50% (wt/v) trichloroacetic acid (50 μL) and then strained for 30 min with 0.4% (wt/v) SRB dissolved in 1% acetic acid. Unbound dye was removed by repeatedly washing with 1% acetic acid. The protein-bound dye was dissolved in 10 mM Tris-base solution (200 μL) for the determination of optical density (OD) at 570 nm while using a microplate reader. The cytotoxic compound adriamycin was used as a positive control. All of the data were obtained in triplicate and presented as means ± SD. IC50 values were calculated with the SigmaPlot 14.0 software using the nonlinear curve-ﬁtting method. For enzyme inhibitor activity, α-glucosidase was chosen as one of the targets.
